Suggestion

I would have liked to have seen some clarifying figures readily available, like when you said: “This plot shows a fair percentage of apartments have entry-level contracts ranging between $800and$1000 a semester. This is shown in the graphic above by the dark blue bars.” The histogram shows well the general range of prices, but the wordfairseems a bit too subjective and less scientific. To avoid this, I would suggest giving a ratio or percentage, perhaps within parentheses to specify the “fair” figure to which you are referring.

For example: “This plot shows a fair percentage (48%) of apartments have entry-level contracts ranging between $800and$1000a semester. This is shown in the graphic above by the dark blue bars.”

Compliment:

The clarity of displaying your price information with a histogram was well done and a good choice. It pairs well with the scatterplot graph of distance to the Maywaring Center on campus. With these two graphs, one can more easily see the relationship between price and distance from school. Good Job!

I think both of your questions could be worded differently to be more concise. As they are currently standing, they are partially vague. Instead of asking, “So just how much does student housing in Rexburg cost” and “Are apartments close to campus more expensive”, focus on a centralized idea combining both questions. It could be stated something like, “Does the distance from campus have a significant impact on the price of theapartments semester contract” Or you could ask, “Is rent cheaper for single students that married students” These are just some ideas that will cause theviewer to be more engaged in reading your results instead of just thinking, “IfI want to know how much student housing is inRexburg, I’ll look it up.”

I did think you did aphenomenal job withexplainingyour graphical summaries. They were clear and easy to understand. Some graphs could use a little moreexplanation (such as why there are two different shades of blue on the histogram) but I loved the variety of your graphical representation of data. Nice Job!
